hopobject.body: I was born in Australia but grew up in England is jack3d banned in australia More so than the Conservatives or Labour, the Lib Dems have always prided themselves on being a party where the rank-and-file members can call the leadership to heel. Ever since the Coalition was formed, their conference has been billed as a clash between those remaining activists who have never been reconciled to a pact with the Tories, and Nick Clegg. This year is no exception. The decision of Sarah Teather, the MP and former minister, not to stand again as Lib Dem candidate for Brent in London was seen as further evidence of this battle for the party’s conscience, though some dismissed her move as a cynical attempt to make a virtue out of the inevitable loss of her seat at the next election. But she reflects a view that the party has lost touch with its beliefs while failing to achieve its cherished constitutional ambitions, such as Lords reform or PR.
